variation.name: ComplexHypercubeInheritance3
variation.description: Example 11 of the spec shows how inheritance should work. The validation log should be something like this: PrimaryParent: under the extended link http://www.xbrl.org/2003/role/link contains one hypercube with one dimension. That hypercube is invalid. under the extended link http://www.xbrl.org/dim/conf/203/ComplexHypercubeInheritance/role/link2 it contains no hypercubes so no dimensional validation should be performed. The PrimaryParent element is dimensionally invalid. FirstChild (incorrectly called FirstChildren) under the extended link http://www.xbrl.org/2003/role/link contains two hypercubes: Cube1 contains just one dimension DimensionOne and Cube2 contains just one dimension DimensionTwo. Both hypercubes are invalid so. The element is dimensionally invalid. under the extended link http://www.xbrl.org/dim/conf/203/ComplexHypercubeInheritance/role/link2 it contains no hypercubes so no dimensional validation should be performed. The FirstChild element is dimensionally invalid. SecondChild (incorrectly called SecondChildren) under the extended link http://www.xbrl.org/2003/role/link contains two hypercubes: Cube1 contains just one dimension DimensionOne and Cube2 contains just one dimension DimensionTwo. Both hypercubes are invalid so. The element is dimensionally invalid. The SecondChild element is dimensionally invalid. ThirdChild (incorrectly called ThirdChildren) under the extended link http://www.xbrl.org/2003/role/link contains two hypercubes: Cube1 contains just one dimension DimensionOne and Cube2 contains just one dimension DimensionTwo. Both hypercubes are invalid so. The element is dimensionally invalid. under the extended link http://www.xbrl.org/dim/conf/203/ComplexHypercubeInheritance/role/link2 it contains just one hypercube Cube3 with one dimension DimensionThree. The cube is dimensionally invalid. The ThirdChild element is dimensionally invalid. There are 4 errors represented because none of the primary items to validate are dimensionally valid. IMHO you are considering the elements "PrimaryParent" and "FirstChild" dimensionally valid because they contain no hypercubes in the extended link http://www.xbrl.org/dim/conf/203/ComplexHypercubeInheritance/role/link2 and according to the spec a primary item with no hypercubes is dimensionally valid. The issue here is whether or not "PrimaryParent" and "FirstChild" contains hypercubes in the extended link http://www.xbrl.org/dim/conf/203/ComplexHypercubeInheritance/role/link2. I'm considering that those two elements do not contain hypercubes in the second extended link because the hypercube inheritance goes from top to bottom only. Therefore, ThirdChild do inherit the hypercubes from PrimaryParent because PrimaryParent is the head of the hierarchy.

variation.name: combinationOfCubesCase7BothOpen
variation.description: The primary item contains two hypercubes, both have closed=false. The instance document uses the one dimension value element from the 'notAll' hypercube and an additional one to satisfy the 'all' hypercube. Since the 'notAll' hypercube is open it is thus considered hypercube valid, which means that the negated result (as this is a 'notAll' hypercube) is invalid.

variation.name: combinationOfCubesCase8NotAllClosed
variation.description: The primary item contains two hypercubes, the 'all' cube with closed=false, the 'notAll' with closed=true. The 'all' hypercube is correctly satisfied. The instance document uses the dimension value element prohibited by the 'notAll' hypercube but this hypercube does not include one of the dimensions declared in the 'all' hypercube; because it is considered closed=true the 'notAll' hypercube is thus considered hypercube invalid, which means that the negated result (as this is a 'notAll' hypercube) is valid.

variation.name: closedHypercubeAndDefaultMembers

variation.name: inheritanceSharedCube-p3-c1
variation.description: Test of Spec Example 11, to determine whether hypercubes are being "shared" across base set networks. Valid in Example 11 strict sense because p3 inherits from both base sets link1 and link2, and here in base set link1 there a single hybercube hc1 with dim1_elt1 its only member, which matches context c1. If dimensional processor were to "share" the hypercubes across all, then hc2 might be processed when inheriting from link1.

variation.name: inheritanceSharedCube-p3-c2

Valid in Example 11 strict sense because base set link2 has a two hybercubes hc1 with dim1_elt2 its only member and hc2 with dim2_elt1, that matches context c1. In a sharing situation a processor may attempt to assure that link1's hc1 entry were valid here too, and fail this case.

variation.name: inheritanceOfClosedAttr-p3-c2closed

A processor inheriting hc1 & hc2 in link2closed, and flipping the closed attribute, thinking it open, would not complain that two mutually exclusive hypercubes are invalid here, each with other's dim being extraneous.

variation.name: inheritanceOfClosedAttr-p3-c2open
variation.description: Test that closed attribute is inherited by primary item inheritance of hypercubes (not explicity in XDT yet). A processor inheriting hc1 & hc2 in link2open, and flipping the closed attribute, thinking it closed, would complain that each cube then being mutually exclusive, has invalid extra content here.

variation.name: inheritanceUsableAttr-p1-c1
variation.description: Test that usable=false attribute is not processed when determining primary item inheritance. This attribute is specified for purposes of exclusion of members from effective domains, and although it may appear on a domain-member arc which somehow gets into a primary item inheritance DRS, such as by targetRole sharing in different base set from where it may participate in specifying hypercube domain members, it isn't to be processed when traversed for purposes of primary item inheritance. In this case the hypercube hc1 would be unseen if some processor utilized the usable=false on primary item inheritance, when evaluating the primary item ancestors in base set for p3 in link1, in which case p1-c1 would be valid, but if hc1 is seen as it should be in the link1 base set, dim1_elt1 is unusable and should generate the error.

variation.name: EmptyDimensionAndNotAllHypercube-2
variation.description: Test the content of an empty dimension. The instance is valid because the hypercube is invalid and linked with a notAll relationship to the primary item. The dimension content is a QName corresponding to a global element defined in a schema. The schema is in the DTS. The QName is the hypercube definition.

variation.name: EmptyDimensionAndNotAllHypercube-3
variation.description: Test the content of an empty dimension. The instance is valid because the hypercube is invalid and linked with a notAll relationship to the primary item. The dimension content is a QName corresponding to a global element defined in a schema. The schema is in the DTS. The QName is the primary item definition.

variation.name: closedNotEmptyHypercubeIsInvalid
variation.description: Point 3.1.3 Fig 4 row 5. It is invalid because the hypercube is closed and contains non expected information

variation.name: openNotEmptyHypercubeIsValid
variation.description: Point 3.1.3 Fig 4 row 6. It is valid because the hypercube is open

variation.name: closedAllOpenNotallWithDefaultsValid1
variation.description: From discussion betw. Bernard, Herm and Michele at CEBS Madrid 2009-04. Two dimensions, each with default total member, and child member, in closed hypercube. First dimension also an open notAll hypercube to exclude first dimensions child member. This test case has both dimensions defaulted, dim1 does not match the notAll cube member, dim2 slips through the notAll's openness, so it is valid.

variation.name: closedAllOpenNotallWithDefaultsValid2
variation.description: Same as V-301 but this test case has only dim1 default, dim2 child, the notAll cube doesn't match dim1 and dim2 slips through the notAll's openness, so it is valid.

variation.name: closedAllOpenNotallWithDefaultsInvalid3
variation.description: Same as V-301 but this test case has no default, dim1 child excluded, invalid.
